<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,151,1592]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1387,1412]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named in honor of mutillid researcher and mentor to KAW, James P. Pitts, and loosely references the pit-like felt line of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,151,1592]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1459,1484]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Remarks.</emphasis>
The felt line of this species (
<figureCitation box="[644,740,1459,1484]" captionStart="FIGURES 147–154" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1148,1171]" captionTargetBox="[169,1417,193,1127]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[169,1417,193,1127]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 147–154. Mutillinae: Trogaspidiini females IV. 147–151. Trogaspidia pittsi, sp. nov.; 152–154. T. lingnani. 147, 152. Habitus, dorsal view; 148, 153. Habitus, lateral view; 149. Face view; 150. Felt line; 151, 154. T6." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2669953/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 150</figureCitation>
) resembles that of many Oriental 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1899" box="[1126,1290,1459,1484]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Odontomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1126,1290,1459,1484]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Odontomutilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. The mesosomal shape and defined pygidium, however, clearly place this species in the Trogaspdiini. We chose to place it in 
<emphasis box="[211,345,1531,1556]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Trogaspidia</emphasis>
because that genus currently holds the greatest diversity and variability in the tribe, but the peculiarities of its felt line and pygidium (
<figureCitation box="[622,717,1567,1592]" captionStart="FIGURES 147–154" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1148,1171]" captionTargetBox="[169,1417,193,1127]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[169,1417,193,1127]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 147–154. Mutillinae: Trogaspidiini females IV. 147–151. Trogaspidia pittsi, sp. nov.; 152–154. T. lingnani. 147, 152. Habitus, dorsal view; 148, 153. Habitus, lateral view; 149. Face view; 150. Felt line; 151, 154. T6." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2669953/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 151</figureCitation>
) suggest that this placement is tenuous.
</paragraph>
